# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-pages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-pages/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:cloudflare-pages/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:cloudflare-pages/jamstack] In JAMstack websites, the application logic typically resides on the client side (for example, an embedded e-commerce checkout service that interacts with pre-rendered static content), without being tightly coupled to a backend server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/jamstack] JAMstack sites are usually served with a Git-based or headless CMS.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] A **static web page**, sometimes called a **flat page** or a **stationary page**, is a web page that is delivered to a web browser exactly as stored, in contrast to dynamic web pages which are generated by a web application.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Consequently, a static web page displays the same information for all users, from all contexts, subject to modern capabilities of a web server to negotiate content-type or language of the document where such versions are available and the server is configured to do so.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] However, a webpage's JavaScript can introduce dynamic functionality which may make the static web page dynamic.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Static web pages are often HTML documents, stored as files in the file system and made available by the web server over HTTP (nevertheless URLs ending with ".html" are not always static).
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] However, loose interpretations of the term could include web pages stored in a database, and could even include pages formatted using a template and served through an application server, as long as the page served is unchanging and presented essentially as stored.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] The content of static web pages remains stationary irrespective of the number of times it is viewed.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Such web pages are suitable for the contents that rarely need to be updated, though modern web template systems are changing this.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Maintaining large numbers of static pages as files can be impractical without automated tools, such as static site generators.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Any personalization or interactivity has to run client-side, which is restricting.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Cloud-based website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, offer no-code platforms for creating static and dynamic web pages through graphical interfaces, without requiring programming expertise.
[src:cloudflare-pages/static-web-page] Static site generators are applications that compile static websites - typically populating HTML templates in a predefined folder and file structure, with content supplied in a format such as Markdown or AsciiDoc.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A **web hosting service** is a type of Internet hosting service that hosts websites for clients, i.e. it offers the facilities required for them to create and maintain a site and makes it accessible on the World Wide Web.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Companies providing web hosting services are sometimes called *web hosts*.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Until 1991, the Internet was restricted to use only "... for research and education in the sciences and engineering ..." and was used for email, telnet, FTP and USENET traffic—but only a tiny number of web pages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The World Wide Web protocols had only just been written, and there wouldn't be a graphical web browser for Mac or Windows computers until the end of 1993.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Even after there was some opening up of Internet access, the situation was confused until 1995.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] To host a website on the internet, an individual or company would need their own computer or server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] As not all companies had the budget or expertise to do this, web hosting services began to offer to host users' websites on their own servers, without the client needing to own the necessary infrastructure required to operate the website.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The owners of the websites, also called webmasters, would be able to create a website that would be hosted on the web hosting service's server and published to the web by the web hosting service.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] As the number of users on the World Wide Web grew, the pressure for companies, both large and small, to have an online presence grew.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] By 1995, companies such as GeoCities, Angelfire and Tripod were offering free hosting.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Static web page files can be uploaded via File Transfer Protocol (FTP) or a web interface, or automatically deployed from a repository using a Continuous Integration tool.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] For example, static page hosting services such as GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages often build directly from source control systems such as Git.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The files are usually delivered to the Web "as is", or with minimal processing, e.g. by using a static site generator such as 11ty.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Many Internet service providers (ISPs) offer this service free to subscribers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Individuals and organizations may also obtain web page hosting from alternative service providers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Free web hosting service is offered by different companies with limited services, sometimes supported by advertisements, and often limited when compared to paid hosting.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Single page hosting is generally sufficient for personal web pages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Personal website hosting is typically free, advertisement-sponsored, or inexpensive.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Business website hosting often has a higher expense depending upon the size and type of the site.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting is using peer-to-peer networking to distribute access to webpages.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This is differentiated from the client–server model which involves the distribution of web data between dedicated web servers and user-end client computers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting may also take the form of P2P web caches and content delivery networks.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A complex site calls for a more comprehensive package that provides database support and application development platforms (e.g.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] ASP.NET, ColdFusion, Java EE, Perl/Plack, PHP or Ruby on Rails).
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] These facilities allow customers to write or install scripts for applications like forums and content management.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Web hosting packages often include a web content management system, so the end-user does not have to worry about the more technical aspects.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) is used for websites that wish to encrypt the transmitted data.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Internet hosting services can run web servers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The scope of web hosting services varies greatly.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] One's website is placed on the same server as many other sites, ranging from a few sites to hundreds of websites.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The features available with this type of service can be quite basic and not flexible in terms of software and updates.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] often sell shared web hosting and web companies often have reseller accounts to provide hosting for clients.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Allows clients to become web hosts themselves.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Resellers could function, for individual domains, under any combination of these listed types of hosting, depending on who they are affiliated with as a reseller.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Resellers' accounts may vary tremendously in size: they may have their own virtual dedicated server to a colocated server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Many resellers provide a nearly identical service to their provider's shared hosting plan and provide the technical support themselves.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] (VPS), divides server resources into virtual servers, where resources can be allocated in a way that does not directly reflect the underlying hardware.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] VPS will often be allocated resources based on a one server to many VPSs relationship, however virtualisation may be done for a number of reasons, including the ability to move a VPS container between servers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Customers are sometimes responsible for patching and maintaining the server (unmanaged server) or the VPS provider may provide server admin tasks for the customer (managed server).
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, the user typically does not own the server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] One type of dedicated hosting is self-managed or unmanaged.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This is usually the least expensive for dedicated plans.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The user has full administrative access to the server, which means the client is responsible for the security and maintenance of their own dedicated server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The user gets their own web server but is not allowed full control over it (user is denied root access for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, they are allowed to manage their data via FTP or other remote management tools.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The user is disallowed full control so that the provider can guarantee quality of service by not allowing the user to modify the server or potentially create configuration problems.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The user typically does not own the server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Similar to the dedicated web hosting service, but the user owns the colo server; the hosting company provides physical space that the server takes up and takes care of the server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This is the most powerful and expensive type of web hosting service.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] In most cases, the colocation provider may provide little to no support directly for their client's machine, providing only the electrical, Internet access, and storage facilities for the server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] In most cases for colo, the client would have their own administrator visit the data center on site to do any hardware upgrades or changes.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] enclosures and standard system configurations.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Hosting based on clustered load-balanced servers.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A cloud hosted website may be more reliable than alternatives since other computers in the cloud can compensate when a single piece of hardware goes down.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Also, local power disruptions or even natural disasters are less problematic for cloud hosted sites, as cloud hosting is decentralized.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting also allows providers to charge users only for resources consumed by the user, rather than a flat fee for the amount the user expects they will use, or a fixed cost upfront hardware investment.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting users can request additional resources on-demand such as only during periods of peak traffic, while offloading IT management to the cloud hosting service.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Having multiple servers hosting the same content for better resource utilization.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Clustered servers are a perfect solution for high-availability dedicated hosting, or creating a scalable web hosting solution.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A cluster may separate web serving from database hosting capability.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] (Usually web hosts use clustered hosting for their shared hosting plans, as there are multiple benefits to the mass managing of clients).
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This form of distributed hosting is when a server cluster acts like a grid and is composed of multiple nodes.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] These can be purpose-built machines or more commonly old PCs.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The host may also provide an interface or control panel for managing the web server and installing scripts, as well as other modules and service applications like e-mail.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A web server that does not use a control panel for managing the hosting account, is often referred to as a "headless" server.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Some hosts specialize in certain software or services (e.g. e-commerce, blogs, etc.).
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The availability of a website is measured by the percentage of a year in which the website is publicly accessible and reachable via the Internet.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This is different from measuring the uptime of a system.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Uptime refers to the system itself being online.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Uptime does not take into account being able to reach it as in the event of a network outage.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] A hosting provider's Service Level Agreement (SLA) may include a certain amount of scheduled downtime per year in order to perform maintenance on the systems.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] This scheduled downtime is often excluded from the SLA timeframe, and needs to be subtracted from the Total Time when availability is calculated.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Depending on the wording of an SLA, if the availability of a system drops below that in the signed SLA, a hosting provider often will provide a partial refund for time lost.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] How downtime is determined changes from provider to provider, therefore reading the SLA is imperative.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Not all providers release uptime statistics.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Because web hosting services host websites belonging to their customers, online security is an important concern.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] When a customer agrees to use a web hosting service, they are relinquishing control of the security of their site to the company that is hosting the site.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] The level of security that a web hosting service offers is extremely important to a prospective customer and can be a major factor when considering which provider a customer may choose.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] Web hosting servers can be attacked by malicious users in different ways, including uploading malware or malicious code onto a hosted website.
[src:cloudflare-pages/web-hosting-service] These attacks may be done for different reasons, including stealing credit card data, launching a Distributed Denial of Service Attack (DDoS) or spamming.
